        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Garland, TX: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Garland, TX, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Garland Fire Department. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the International Fire Code (IFC) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Garland Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Garland enforces the International Fire Code (IFC), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Garland is one of the DFW metroplex's largest industrial and manufacturing cities, with significant operations in the Garland Industrial Park along Miller Road and Shiloh Road. The city's large Vietnamese-American and Asian community has created a concentration of restaurants and commercial kitchens in the International District along Walnut Street. Industrial facilities — metal fabrication, plastics manufacturing, electronics assembly — carry specific Class B and Class C extinguisher requirements beyond standard commercial.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. Texas requires fire extinguisher service to be performed by a technician licensed through the Texas Department of Insurance (TDI) State Fire Marshal's Office. Verify your service provider holds a current Portable Fire Extinguisher license at tdi.texas.gov/fire. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Garland Fire Department commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
